cialized subjects of US economic aid and development. Samoan players succeed by becoming entrepreneurs: building and commodifying their bodies and brands to enhance their football stock and market value. Uperesa offers insights into the social and physical costs of pursuing a football career, the structures that compel Pacific Islander youth toward athletic labor, and the possibilities for safeguarding their health and wellbeing in the future.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aFootball playerszAmerican Samoa. 0aFootballxEconomic aspectszAmerican Samoa. 0aFootballxSocial aspectszAmerican Samoa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aFutures, Niu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022701?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022701/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles